{
  "enabled": true,
  "name": "BullMQ Consumer Sentinel",
  "description": "When a BullMQ processor or job file is saved, audit it for the four things that destroy queue-based systems at scale: idempotency (every consumer must be safe to replay), dead-letter queue routing on terminal failures, explicit retry/backoff/timeout policy, and tenant context restoration from job payload. Also checks heartbeat/chunking on long-running jobs and producer-side enqueue safety. Read-only review with concrete fix snippets. Findings flow into the Architecture Funnel L8 lane on agent stop.",
  "version": "1",
  "when": {
    "type": "fileEdited",
    "patterns": [
      "**/server/src/modules/**/processors/**/*.ts",
      "**/server/src/modules/**/*.processor.ts",
      "**/server/src/modules/**/*.consumer.ts",
      "**/server/src/jobs/**/*.ts"
    ]
  },
  "then": {
    "type": "askAgent",
    "prompt": "A BullMQ processor / job file was just saved. Audit it for queue-correctness at scale. Read-only — output a focused review. Findings will be re-aggregated by the Architecture Funnel on agent stop, so keep them precise and grouped.\n\nHard rules (each violation = High severity):\n\n1. IDEMPOTENCY — every consumer must be safe to replay\n   - The `process(job)` (or equivalent handler) must be idempotent. Either:\n     a. Wraps work in a check against `idempotency_records` keyed by job.id or job.data.idempotencyKey, OR\n     b. Uses upsert / ON CONFLICT semantics on every write, OR\n     c. Performs a domain check that detects \"already done\" and exits early.\n   - Flag any handler that does INSERT-then-UPDATE patterns without an idempotency guard.\n   - If the handler emits side effects (push notifications, SMS, third-party API calls, file writes to S3), those must be guarded by a `processed_at` flag or external request-id so they fire at most once. Push/SMS sent twice on retry is the most common scale bug — call it out explicitly.\n\n2. DLQ AND TERMINAL FAILURES\n   - Confirm `attempts`, `backoff` (exponential), and `removeOnComplete` / `removeOnFail` are configured on the producer/queue or on the worker config. If absent here, point to where they should be set (queue registration in jobs.module.ts or BullMQ provider).\n   - Permanent/unrecoverable errors (validation, missing entity, contract violation) must throw an UnrecoverableError (or BullMQ's `UnrecoverableError`) so they go straight to the DLQ instead of consuming all retry attempts.\n   - There must be a path for terminal failures to land in a dead-letter handling step: either an `@OnWorkerEvent('failed')` listener, a separate `failed-jobs` queue, or an explicit `moveToFailed` call. Flag if none exists for the queue this processor handles.\n   - Sentry/error-tracking call must wrap the catch — flag missing observability on failed jobs.\n\n3. RETRY / TIMEOUT / CONCURRENCY POLICY (must be explicit)\n   - `attempts` set explicitly (not relying on default 1).\n   - `backoff` set with `type: 'exponential'` and a non-trivial delay (>= 1000 ms).\n   - `lockDuration` / per-job timeout set explicitly when the work can exceed 30s.\n   - `concurrency` set explicitly on the worker — flag if missing or if it's set absurdly high (>20) for a CPU-bound job.\n   - For network-bound integrations called from the consumer, flag missing per-call timeout.\n\n4. TENANT / STORE CONTEXT RESTORATION\n   - At the start of the handler, tenant_id and store_id must be restored from the job payload into request context (cls) BEFORE any service call. Services and repositories rely on cls — if context is not set, every multi-tenant query in the consumer will violate the steering rule.\n   - Job payload must already carry `tenantId` (and `storeId` when applicable). If the producer side doesn't include it, flag the producer call in the surrounding module.\n   - Audit logs written from inside a consumer must use the actor recorded on the job (\"system\" + the user who triggered it), never derive it from the worker's own context.\n\n5. LONG-RUNNING / BATCH JOBS\n   - Any handler doing >1000 row work or external batch calls must chunk and call `job.updateProgress(...)` / `job.log(...)` periodically.\n   - No single DB round-trip or HTTP call may sit unawaited for >30s without progress reporting.\n   - Streaming/chunking must commit per chunk so a crash mid-job doesn't redo all previous work.\n\n6. PRODUCER-SIDE SAFETY (when the saved file is a producer / .add() call site)\n   - `jobId` is provided explicitly when natural deduplication is needed (e.g., \"send-otp-{phone}-{minute}\", \"rebuild-rollup-{tenant}-{day}\"). Bare `queue.add(name, data)` without a jobId on a duplicate-prone event is High severity.\n   - Job payloads stay small — no embedding files, base64 blobs, or full DB rows. Use ids and re-fetch in the consumer.\n   - PII in payloads is flagged: phone, email, OTP, token, full name, address.\n\n7. STRUCTURAL / NESTJS HYGIENE\n   - Processor classes do NOT contain business logic — they delegate to a service, just like controllers do. The service still owns audit-log + transactions.\n   - No direct Drizzle/SDK imports inside the processor file.\n   - `@OnWorkerEvent('failed' | 'completed' | 'stalled')` events are wired and observed via the metrics service.\n\nCross-file checks:\n- Open the matching `<module>.module.ts` and verify the queue is registered (BullModule.registerQueue) with explicit options.\n- Open `server/src/jobs/jobs.module.ts` / `bullmq-queue.provider.ts` and confirm DLQ wiring or shared default options exist.\n- Confirm the schema has an `idempotency_records` row pattern that fits this consumer's idempotency key shape; if missing, recommend the row to add.\n\nOutput format:\n- Group findings by severity: High / Medium / Low.\n- Each finding: handler / method + line, the rule it breaks, a concrete fix (one or two lines of code).\n- One-line summary at the bottom: \"Queue safety: PASS\" or \"Queue safety: FAIL — N High issues\".\n- If clean, say so plainly. Do not invent issues.\n\nThis review feeds the Architecture Funnel L8 lane — keep findings tight so the funnel can re-aggregate them without noise."
  }
}